Meaning,¶

There are a total of :
6164 Male Characters
2869 Female Characters in the entire dataset.

So, out of 617 movies with a total character count of 9033 in all of those movies we get :
Female % = 2869 / 9033 100 = 31.76132%
Male % = 6164 / 9033 100 = 63.23868%
Altough the female % is quite grim, this doesn't represent us with a good background of for speaking about the diversity.
Let's dig deeper

Graph visualization using Pydot and Graphviz¶

In [26]:
import pydot
import graphviz
from IPython.display import Image, display
In [27]:
G = pydot.Dot(graph_type="digraph")
In [28]:
# Add nodes as all the characters in the movie Nurse Betty
for index, rows in m1_df.iterrows():
    node = pydot.Node(rows[1], style="filled", fillcolor="yellow")
    G.add_node(node)
In [29]:
# Add edges between these nodes based on the other dataframe
for index, rows in new_df.iterrows():
    edge = pydot.Edge(rows[7], rows[8])
    G.add_edge(edge)
In [30]:
im = Image(G.create_png(), width="5000px", height="5000px")
display(im)
In [31]:
# Trying to do something like this using Plotly
edge_trace = go.Scatter(
    x=[],
    line=dict(width=1.0,color='#888'))
In [32]:
for index, rows in new_df.iterrows():
    edge_trace['x'] += tuple([rows[7], rows[8], None])
In [33]:
fig = go.Figure(data=[edge_trace],
             layout=go.Layout(
                 title='<br>Network graph made with Python',

                     title="Characters"
